Hello Scott! Try to use heading elements in order. Using heading elements in order provides a better structure to your webpage.

If the next heading size (`<h3>` in this case) is too big, you can use CSS to override the default font size. Like this:
```
h3 {
  font-size: 0.67em;
}
```

You can find the [default values for heading elements here](https://www.w3.org/TR/html5/rendering.html#sections-and-headings)

[Learn more about heading elements here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/Heading_Elements)

This part of your prediction step could be refactored to avoid constructing new `normal_dsitribution` objects for every particle. You could define a single set of 3 `normal_dsitribution` objects (one each for `x`, `y`, and `theta`) all centred around 0. You can then add the noise to each property for each particle. This is an example of what this would look like for just the `x` property:

```
normal_distribution<double> dist_x(0, std_pos[0]);
// Enter the loop and calculate the new value of `x`...
particles[i].x += dist_x(gen);
```

