This is more a matter of preference and convention, but typically classes and IDs are lowercase and when they contain two words a dash `-` is added. Like this:
```
.project-footer {
  border-top: 1px solid hsla(0, 0%, 0%, 0.3);
  padding-top: 20px;
  margin-top: 20px;
}
```

Tip: If you rename a selector here, be sure to update the HTML too.

This will throw an error if we search for a book that has no authors.  You can replicate this by typing in "dog" or "test" for example.  You will get the following error in your logcat:

> org.json.JSONException: No value for authors

We can check if a JSONObject has a field or not by using the `.has()` method.  We can use that method to make sure we don't try to grab a value that doesn't exist.

    if(volumeInfo.has("authors")){
        //parse here
    }

like that!

Another option is to use `optJSONArray()` instead of `getJSONArray()`.  This method is used to parse fields that may or may not be present, and won't throw a `JSONException` if it is not present :smile:

### Code Quality ###
Code is not readable yet. Indentation is not consistent in general.

All inconsistent indentation must be fixed to help others reading, editing your code.

Please refer to example below to help you re-indent the code.

## Example

```
body {
  height: 100%;
  padding: 0;
  margin: 0;
}

header {
  padding-top: 29px;
  background-color: #786;
  width: 100%;
  text-align: center;
  padding-bottom: 5px;
  margin-bottom: 5px;
}

#map {
  height: 700px;
  width: 100%;
}

p {
  margin-top: 0;
  text-align: center;
}

#inputClass {
  width: 90%;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
  text-indent: inherit;
}

.outputList {
  width: 90%;
  vertical-align: center;
}

a {
  padding-right: 5px;
  padding-left: 5px;
  padding-bottom: 5px;
  padding-top: 5px;
  display: block;
  border: 3px solid #408;
  font-weight: bold;
}

h1 {
  color: #525454;
  font-size: 36px;
  margin: 0 0 10px 0;
  line-height: 40px;
  text-align: center;
}

h2 {
  font-size: 30px;
  line-height: 40px;
}

h3 {
  font-size: 24px;
  line-height: 40px;
  text-align: center;
}

h4 {
  font-size: 18px;
  line-height: 20px;
}

/* Won't be used here */

h5 {
  font-size: 14px;
  line-height: 20px;
}

h6 {
  font-size: 12px;
  line-height: 20px;
}

#pano {
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
}
```

## For Future Reference :zap:

I strongly recommend learning the new version of Javascript - ES6 (ECMAScript 6). It has been officially approved and is widely adopted by programmers. Popular frameworks like Angular 2, React, etc. all prioritize ES6 syntax.

ES6 introduces new syntax/concepts, such as:
- `let` / `const` variables
- Arrow functions, eg:
  ```
  let foo = () => {
    // operations
  };
  ```
- Module import
- `Promise` - a new method to deal with asynchronous task (instead of the old callback function)
- New way to implement Classes, eg:
  ```
  class Foo {
    constructor(num) {
      this.num = num;
    }

    addNum(a) {
      return this.num += a;
    }
  }
  ```
- And many more... :star2:

### Resources :books
- [ES6 - JavaScript Improved @Udacity](https://www.udacity.com/course/es6-javascript-improved--ud356)
- [Beginners ES6 and Babel Tutorial @HTML5 Hive](https://html5hive.org/es6-and-babel-tutorial/)
- [ECMAScript 6 Tutorial by ccoenraets](http://ccoenraets.github.io/es6-tutorial/)

Note that ES6 is usually used with Babel compiler (and a build process, such as `webpack`, `gulp`, etc.) for browser compatability fallback. So you will also learn about them in the resources above.

